  "opinion": "As a school teacher in Los Angeles with a master's degree and a background in education, I've witnessed firsthand how stereotype threat manifests in STEM classrooms. It's not just about students fearing they'll confirm negative stereotypes; it's the subtle weight of expectations that can make them doubt their own abilities. I've seen it in the way some students avoid math problems because they believe they're 'not good at it,' or how girls hesitate to speak up in physics discussions, convinced they'll be judged for their lack of understanding. As someone who grew up in a family that valued education but didn't emphasize STEM fields, I understand the tension between societal expectations and personal potential. Stereotype threat is real and it harms students, especially those from underrepresented groups. We absolutely must address it—through inclusive teaching practices, mentorship programs, and creating environments where every student feels safe to explore their interests without fear of judgment. In my classroom, I actively work to dismantle these barriers by normalizing diverse perspectives and celebrating successes across all disciplines. This isn't just about fairness; it's about nurturing the next generation of innovators who can thrive in a world that increasingly demands STEM skills. I believe in the power of small, consistent actions—like asking students to share their personal connections to STEM or highlighting role models from all backgrounds—to build confidence and challenge the very idea that certain fields are 'for' some people and not others. The key is to make learning feel personal and relevant, so that students don't just survive but truly flourish in STEM.",
